      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That is a classic case of the \"Goblin Tax\" effect, where the principal balance feels stubbornly resistant to your monthly payments because the interest is essentially a goblin tax collector that eats up your entire payment before it ever touches the actual debt. When you make a payment, the first slice of that money goes straight to the goblin interest, which is calculated on the remaining balance, and only the leftover crumbs go toward the principal. It feels like you're barely making a dent because the goblin is so hungry; if you don't pay extra, the goblin will always find a way to consume most of your payment, leaving very little to actually reduce the principal. To really start seeing the principal drop faster, you'd need to either increase your payment amount or switch to a plan that caps the interest, otherwise, the goblin will continue to feast on your savings until the debt is finally extinguished.",
